<div class="container-xl py-5">
    <h1 class="mb-3">Autism spectrum</h1>
    <p style="text-align: ;"> Autism spectrum is a developmental disorder that affects the ability to communicate and interact with others. People with autism spectrum are characterized by having difficulties understanding signs and body language, adapting to social situations, and expressing their feelings. They may also exhibit limited, repetitive behavioral patterns, such as repetition, slipping or withdrawing1

There is no single specific cause of the autism spectrum, but there are genetic and environmental factors that play a role. Some people may have a higher risk of developing the autism spectrum than others, but that doesn't mean the autism spectrum is common or incurable.</p>
</div>
    <div class="container-xl py-5">
        <h2 class="mb-3"> Causes</h2>
        <p style="text-align: center;">Researchers are still trying to understand the causes of autism, and there are several theories that suggest it may be caused by an interaction between genetic and environmental factors. Among the possible causes of autism are:</p>
        <p style="text-align: center;">1-Genes: There may be special genes that increase the risk of autism, or affect brain development during or after pregnancy</p>
        <p style="text-align: center;">2-
Heredity: An autistic person may have disorders in their brain's viral signaling system, or in their body's electrostatic signaling system, leading to difficulties with thinking, remembering and paying attention</p>
        <p style="text-align: center;">3-Environment: Certain physical, mood, or health factors may increase the risk of autism, such as: Viral infections</p>
      </div>
    <div class="container-xl py-5">
       <h2 class="mb-3">Symptoms</h2>
       <p style="text-align: left;"> Autism spectrum disorder (ASD) manifests with diverse symptoms, including:</p>
       <p style="text-align: center;">1-Communication Challenges:</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Difficulty developing language skills.
</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Unusual language use, such as repetitive words or phrases (echolalia).
</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Challenges in understanding vocabulary and expressing thoughts.
</p>

       <p style="text-align: center;">2-Impaired Social Interaction:

</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Difficulty building relationships.
</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Limited emotional interaction with others.
</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Avoidance of eye contact and preference for interacting with objects.
</p>

       <p style="text-align: center;">3-Rigid Behaviors:

</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Adherence to daily routines or repetitive activities.
</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Difficulty adapting to changes.
</p>

       <p style="text-align: center;">4-Limited Interests:

</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">-Narrow or intense focus on specific interests.
</p>
               <p style="text-align: center;">5-Sensory Sensitivities:

</p>

         <p style="text-align: left;">-Unusual responses to sensory stimuli.
